.TH ANNUITY_PRICING 1 "2026-06-23" "finance/planning/annuity" "Annuity Planning Tools"
.SH NAME
annuity_pricing \- price a single-premium immediate annuity from SOA mortality tables
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B python annuity_pricing.py
.I amount age gender
.RB [ --joint-age
.IR AGE ]
.RB [ --joint-gender
.IR M|F ]
.RB [ --interest
.IR RATE ]
.RB [ --improvement ]
.RB [ --quote-year
.IR YEAR ]
.PP
.B python annuity_pricing.py --compare
.RB [ --state
.IR CODE ]
.RB [ --interest
.IR RATE ]
.RB [ --improvement ]
.RB [ --quote-year
.IR YEAR ]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B annuity_pricing.py
prices a single-premium immediate annuity (SPIA) \(em the level lifetime income a
lump sum buys \(em from a mortality table and a flat interest rate. It is a
self-contained actuarial calculation with no network access, and serves as the
default annuity-payout engine for
.BR withdrawal_projection (1)
and
.BR montecarlo (1).
.PP
Two products are priced:
.IP \(bu 2
a
.I single-life
annuity, paying for one life, and
.IP \(bu 2
a
.I last-survivor
annuity for two lives, paying as long as
.I either
person is alive (joint and 100% survivor).
.PP
The return value of each is the
.I annual
payout (the sum of twelve monthly payments) on the given premium. Because the
payout is linear in the premium, the rate computed for one dollar scales to any
amount.
.SH METHOD
With a flat interest rate \fIi\fR and survival probabilities \fItpx\fR from the
mortality table, the actuarial present value of $1 per year of income (paid
monthly, in arrears, while alive) is
.PP
.RS
.nf
a_x^(12) ~= a_x + 11/24            (Woolhouse 2-term, m = 12)
a_x      = sum_{t>=1} v^t * tpx    (annual annuity-immediate)
v        = 1 / (1 + i)
.fi
.RE
.PP
and the level annual payout is the premium divided by that factor. For two lives
the last-survivor factor follows from inclusion-exclusion,
.RS
.nf
a_LS = a_x + a_y - a_xy            (a_xy pays while BOTH live)
.fi
.RE
with the same +11/24 monthly adjustment; the lives are assumed independent. The
income timing (monthly, first payment in one month) matches the
immediateannuities.com convention, so the two are directly comparable.
.PP
The base mortality is the SOA 2012 IAM table, as of 2012. With
.B --improvement
those rates are projected forward
.I generationally
using Projection Scale G2:
.RS
.nf
q_a(year) = q_a(2012) * (1 - g2_a) ** (year - 2012)
.fi
.RE
applied as each cohort ages, so the calendar year at attained age \fIa\fR is
\fIquote-year\fR + (\fIa\fR \- start age). Improvement lengthens lifespans and so
.I lowers
the payout. Scale G2 grades to zero by its terminal age; attained ages beyond the
G2 table simply receive no further improvement.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.I amount
Premium (starting investment). Accepts plain digits, commas, or a leading "$".
Must be positive.
.TP
.I age
Age today. Integer 0\(en120.
.TP
.I gender
\fBM\fR or \fBF\fR (\fBmale\fR/\fBfemale\fR also accepted). Selects the base
mortality table.
.TP
.BI --joint-age " AGE"
Second life's age (0\(en120). Switches to a last-survivor annuity. Must be given
together with \fB--joint-gender\fR.
.TP
.BI --joint-gender " M|F"
Second life's gender. Must be given together with \fB--joint-age\fR.
.TP
.BI --interest " RATE"
Flat annual interest rate as a decimal fraction (e.g. \fB0.04\fR for 4%). Default
\fB0.035\fR.
.TP
.B --improvement
Apply Scale G2 mortality improvement (generational projection to the quote year).
Requires the G2 tables \fBsoa_mortality_2583.csv\fR (male) and
\fBsoa_mortality_2584.csv\fR (female); a clear error is printed if they are
absent.
.TP
.BI --quote-year " YEAR"
Calendar year to project mortality to for \fB--improvement\fR. Default: the
current year.
.TP
.B --compare
Benchmark the model against live immediateannuities.com quotes for single and
joint annuities at ages 60, 65, 70, and 80 (ignores the positional arguments;
uses a $100,000 premium). Prints model and site annual payouts and their ratio.
Requires network access.
.TP
.BI --state " CODE"
US state for the site quotes fetched by \fB--compare\fR. Default \fBFL\fR.
.SH OUTPUT
For a single pricing run, a line identifying the annuity and parameters, followed
by the annual payout (with its percentage of the premium) and the equivalent
monthly payout. For
.BR --compare ,
a table over the four ages with one row each for single male, single female, and
joint male-and-female, showing the model annual payout, the live site annual
payout, and the model/site ratio.
.SH ASSUMPTIONS AND CAVEATS
.IP \(bu 2
The 2012 IAM rates are
.I annuitant
mortality (annuitants live longer than the general population). The model applies
no insurer expense, profit, or interest-rate load, so at a given interest rate it
prices a clean actuarial benchmark, not a marketed quote.
.IP \(bu 2
At the default 3.5% the model pays noticeably less than current market quotes;
empirically it matches immediateannuities.com at roughly 5% interest, i.e. the
site's current quotes imply about a 5% pricing rate. Use
.B --compare
to see the gap for your own ages.
.IP \(bu 2
The two lives of a last-survivor annuity are assumed independent (no common-shock
or broken-heart adjustment).
.IP \(bu 2
The table's top age (120) is treated as certain death, so the survival curve
terminates there.
.SH EXAMPLES
.PP
Single-life annuity for a 65-year-old male, $100,000, default 3.5%:
.PP
.RS
.nf
python annuity_pricing.py 100000 65 M
.fi
.RE
.PP
Last-survivor annuity for a 65-year-old male and 63-year-old female:
.PP
.RS
.nf
python annuity_pricing.py 100000 65 M --joint-age 63 --joint-gender F
.fi
.RE
.PP
Single life at 4% interest with Scale G2 mortality improvement:
.PP
.RS
.nf
python annuity_pricing.py 100000 70 F --interest 0.04 --improvement
.fi
.RE
.PP
Benchmark the model against the live site, with improvement applied:
.PP
.RS
.nf
python annuity_pricing.py --compare --improvement
.fi
.RE
.SH FILES
.TP
.B annuity_pricing.py
This program. Exposes \fBsingle_life_annuity()\fR and
\fBlast_survivor_annuity()\fR for reuse (e.g. by \fBwithdrawal_projection\fR(1)).
.TP
.B soa_mortality_2581.csv, soa_mortality_2582.csv
SOA 2012 IAM base mortality tables (male / female): one annual mortality rate per
integer age 0\(en120.
.TP
.B soa_mortality_2583.csv, soa_mortality_2584.csv
SOA Projection Scale G2 improvement tables (male / female), used by
\fB--improvement\fR.
.TP
.B annuity_quote.py
Fetches the live site quotes compared by \fB--compare\fR.
.SH ENVIRONMENT
Run with any of the project's Python 3 interpreters, e.g.
.B ~/finance/planning/.venv/bin/python.
No third-party packages are required. Network access is needed only for
.BR --compare .
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR withdrawal_projection (1),
.BR montecarlo (1),
.BR annuity_quote (1)
.SH AUTHOR
Generated for the personal finance planning workspace.
